title: Matador Cup live scores: Coverage of New South Wales v Victoria at North Sydney Oval
text:
VICTORIA has ended New South Wales’ winning run, beating the Blues by 21 runs in Sunday’s Matador Cup clash at North Sydney Oval.
In a game featuring 13 players who have donned the baggy green, competition leader New South Wales bowled Victoria out for 244 and at one stage it was cruising at 3-159.
The Blues started their chase in impressive fashion, with Nic Maddinson hammering 20 runs off James Pattinson’s second over, hitting a six over the root an onto a car parked outside North Sydney Oval.
An over later Maddinson fell to man of the match John Hastings, trapped in front of the stumps for 20. It was the first of six straigh lbw wickets for Victoria, the final of which left NSW on 6-172 off 37 overs.
In the end NSW’s untested tail was unable to make up the rest of the runs, with Scott Boland bowling Nathan Lyon (1) in the 49th over.
Having already secured a spot in the final, the Blues rested captain Steve Smith, but recalled Starc to a bowling attack that also featured Test stars Josh Hazlewood and Lyon.

Opinion 0 comments Robert Irwin’s animal instinct Celebrity Starc (4-58) struck in the game’s third over, clean bowling Aaron Finch (2), but he had to wait until the 45th over to get his next wicket.
Playing in his first game of the season, opener Rob Quiney scored 79 runs from 75 balls, managing to dull the new-ball attack of Starc and Hazlewood without damaging Victoria’s run rate.
For a while it looked like Quiney was going to be the only batsman to make a stand for the Vics, with Cameron White (27), Glenn Maxwell (5), Peter Handscomb (20) and Dan Christian (1) all falling before the 25th over to leave the Bushrangers at 5-122.
Quiney was the next man to go, stumped off Stephen O’Keefe (1-35), but a quickfire 63 off 65 balls from Matthew Wade ensured the Bushrangers went well past 200.
The Victoria keeper ran out of partners in the end, with Starc knocking over the last three wickets to end Victoria’s innings in the 47th over.
The left-hander has now taken at least four wickets in each of his last seven domestic one-day games and has taken 23 for the season at an average of 7.47
